INFLUENZA UPDATE - NORTHERN HEMISPHERE (05)
*******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Mon 22 Mar 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: World Health Organisation (WHO), WER and Epidemiological Bulletin,
Mon 22 Mar 2004 [edited]
<http://www.who.int/csr/don>

Summary of Global Human Influenza Surveillance
----------------------------------------------
Influenza activity remained low in most parts of the world. Only Hong Kong
SAR China and Japan reported high levels of influenza A (H3N2) virus infection.
Reports from individual countries:
Austria
-------
Influenza A(H3N2) virus activity declined in weeks 9-10 and is reported as
sporadic.
Canada
------
During weeks 9-10, influenza activity was reported as either sporadic or
"no activity" in most parts of Canada, while in Quebec and parts of Nova
Scotia and Newfoundland, localised activity was reported. The
Influenza-like Illness (ILI) consultation rate was below the expected range
for this time of year.
Hong Kong, SAR China
--------------------
Influenza activity continued to increase in weeks 9-10 when a number of
outbreaks in schools were reported. Most of the isolates were identified as
influenza A (H3N2) virus.
Germany
-------
In week 9, influenza A (H3N2) virus activity was reported as regional for
the 2nd week.
Italy
-----
The number of viruses detected continued to decreased in weeks 9-10, and
influenza activity remained at a medium level.
Japan
-----
Influenza activity continued to decrease in weeks 9-10 but was still
reported as regional activity for week 10. From 20 of 47 reporting
prefectures, the ILI consultation rate was below the epidemic threshold.
Latvia
------
Influenza activity declined rapidly in weeks 9-10, reaching baseline.
Sporadic activity was reported for week 10.
Russia Federation
-----------------
Influenza activity continued to decline. In week 9, the influenza morbidity
was below epidemic threshold in all regions under surveillance. In week 10,
no influenza virus was detected.
Switzerland
-----------
The influenza epidemic of this season appeared to be slowly reaching its
end. In week 10, no influenza virus was detected.
United States
-------------
Influenza activity remained low during week 9, when the ILI consultation
rate remained below national baseline, and no reports of widespread
activity were received from individual states. Mortality due to pneumonia
and influenza continued to decline and to be below epidemic threshold for
the 1st time in the past 10 weeks.
Other reports
-------------
During weeks 9-10, low influenza activity was reported in Chile, Denmark,
Madagascar, Norway, Slovenia, Sweden, and the United Kingdom. Argentina,
Belgium, Croatia, and New Caledonia reported no influenza activity.
